Democracy.
We in the West make a big mistake in taking them for granted.
We see democracy not as the fragile plant that it is in reality, but as an inventory of our society.
We tend to think of them as an immutable give-up.
We believe that capitalism inevitably leads to democracy.
That's not true.
Lee Kuan Yew from Singapore and his great imitators in Beijing have proved beyond doubt that it is quite possible to have a thriving capitalism and impressive growth, while the policy remains completely undemocratic.
In fact, democracy is dwindling with us, in Europe.
Earlier this year, when I represented Greece -- the newly elected Greek government -- it was made unequivocally clear to me as finance minister in the Eurogroup that our country's democratic process -- our elections -- should not affect the austerity programs that were realised in Greece.
At that moment, I thought that there might not be a better justification for Lee Kuan Yew or the Chinese Communist Party, or some of my rebellious friends who repeatedly told me that democracy would be abolished if it changed anything.
At this point, I would like to introduce you to an economic model for a true democracy.
I ask you, together with me, to believe again that Lee Kuan Yew, the Chinese Communist Party and even the Eurogroup, are succumbing to a mistaken belief that we could save ourselves democracy, but that we need a true and defensive democracy.
Because without democracy, our societies will be more mean, our future bleak and our great, new technologies are wasted.
On the subject of waste, I would like to draw your attention to an interesting contradiction that is currently threatening our economies.
I call it the "Twin Summit paradox."
A summit is known to you. They know and recognize him as the mountain of debt that casts its long shadow over the US, Europe and the whole world.
We all recognize the mountain of debt,
But few people recognize his twin.
A mountain of unused cash that belongs to wealthy savers and corporations, but which are too afraid to invest where it would be productive and could bring in income, with which you could carry down the mountain of debt and also produce all the things that humanity desperately needs, for example, "green" energy.
I give them two numbers.
In the past 3 months, $3.4 trillion has been invested in the US, in England and the eurozone, combined, in all the wealth-producing goods, such as industrial facilities, machinery, office buildings, schools, roads, tracks, equipment and so on and so forth.
$3.4 trillion sounds like a lot of money until you compare it to the $5.1 trillion that were lying around in the same countries and our financial institutions at the same time, and did absolutely nothing except bloat the exchanges and drive up real estate prices.
Thus, debt and unproductive capital form the twin peaks, which are not balanced by the usual market mechanisms.
The result is stagnant wages, more than a quarter of 25-54-year-olds unemployed in the US, Japan and Europe, and consequently low overall economic demand, which, as in an endless loop, reinforces investor pessimism, which, fearing low demand, promote it themselves, in which they do not invest. Just like Oedipus's father, who, out of fear, the oracle's prophecy, could come true that his son would kill him if he grows up,
Unintentionally, the circumstances that cause Oedipus to kill him.
This is my struggle with capitalism --
its exceedingly wasteful manner. All the unproductive capital should be used to improve our lives, develop human talent and especially finance all the technologies, "green" technologies that are crucial to saving the earth.
Is democracy the solution?
I think so. But before we continue: What do we mean by democracy?
Aristotle defined democracy as the form of society in which the free and the poor as a majority control the government.
Athenian democracy, of course, excluded too many --
Women, foreigners, and of course slaves.
However, it would be a mistake to reduce the importance of Athenian democracy on the basis of these exclusions.
The decisive factor in Athenian democracy was and is that it included the working poor, and not only gave them the right to freedom of expression, but more important and decisive is that it granted them the right to political participation with equal voice weighting in matters of state concerns.
Athenian democracy did not last long --
Like a candle that shines very bright, it is also quickly burned out.
However, our present-day liberal democracies do not have their roots in ancient Athens,
but in the Magna Carta, in the glorious revolution of 1688, even in the American Constitution.
While Athenian democracy focused on the free citizens and strengthened the working poor, our liberal democracy is based on the values of the Magna Carta, which was ultimately a statute for rulers.
Because liberal democracy only came up when a complete separation of politics and the economy was possible and the democratic process narrowed down to politics, while the economy -- that is, the world of corporations -- became a democracy-free zone.
In our democracies today, since the time this separation of politics and economics began, a relentless struggle between the two has taken place, gradually inferring politics and disempowering politics.
Wonder why politicians are no longer the same as they used to be?
It's not because of a degeneration of their DNA.
It's because you can be in government these days and still not in power because power has migrated from politics to the economy and the areas are separate.
I mentioned my struggle with capitalism.
When you think about it, it's about like a herd of predators that has so sustainably decimated the animals it feeds on that it ends up starving.
It is similar with the economy, which has cannibalized politics to such an extent that it harms itself through the self-induced economic crisis. The power of corporations is growing, political goods are being devalued, inequality is increasing, overall economic demand is falling and the managing directors of the corporations are too terrified to invest the cash of their companies.
The more successful capitalism drives the "demos" out of democracy, the higher the twin peaks become, and the greater the waste of human labour power and the prosperity of humanity.
If that is true, it is obvious that we must bring politics and the economy back together, and it would be better if the "demos" retains control, as in ancient Athens, apart from the exclusion of slaves, women and foreigners.
This is not a new idea, by the way.
The Marxist left had this idea 100 years ago and it did not go very well.
The lesson from the debacle of the Soviet Union should be that the working poor regain a position only by a miracle, as in ancient Athens, without creating new kinds of brutality and waste.
But there is a solution: abolish the working poor!
Capitalism does it by replacing low-wage workers with automation and robots.
The problem with this is, as long as economics and politics are separate areas, automation will make the twin peaks higher, the waste of sublime, and the social conflicts deeper, just as it will -- very soon, as I believe -- in countries like China.
So we need to reshape the economy and reunite the areas of economy and politics, taking care that we democratize the reunified area, otherwise we will end up in a pathological surveillance hyperautocracy that makes the film "Matrix" appear like a documentary.
The question, therefore, is not whether capitalism will survive the technical achievements it has produced --
The more interesting question is whether capitalism is replaced by a dystopia, similar to that in "Matrix," or by something that resembles society in "Star Trek," in which machines serve humans and people put their energy into the exploration of the universe, or into a high-tech version of the ancient Athenian "Agora," indulge in the meaning of life in long conversations.
I think we can be optimistic.
So what would it take, what might it look like to have this "Star Trek"-like utopia instead of the "Matrix"-like dystopia?
In the practical implementation, I would like to give you some examples, in a very short time.
In the field of companies: Please imagine a capital market in which you earn money while you work and in which your capital follows you from one job to the next, from one company to the next, and the company -- no matter in which you are currently working -- is the property of those who currently work in the company.
Then all income comes from capital and proceeds, and the concept of wage labour is completely outdated.
No more distinction between those who own the companies, but who do not work in it, and employees who work there, but who do not own the company. No more tug-of-war between capital and labour, no big gaps between investment and saving, and ultimately no outstanding twin summits.
In the field of global political economy: Please briefly imagine that our national currencies would have a freely fluctuating exchange rate, in a universal, global, digital currency issued by the IMF [International Monetary Fund], and the G-20 [Group of 20 Largest Emerging Markets], in the interest of all humanity.
Continue to imagine that all world trade is traded in this currency -- we call it "the cosmos," in units of "cosmos" -- and each government deposits the sum equivalent to the trade deficit or trade surplus of the respective country into a common fund.
Imagine that this fund invests in "green" technologies, especially in parts of the world where investment funds are scarce.
This is not a new idea.
It's basically what John Maynard Keynes had suggested in the 1944 Bretton Woods Conference.
The problem was that at that time it was not necessary to implement the technical means.
Today we have them, especially against the backdrop of a reunified politics and economy.
The world I describe to you is at the same time libertarian, in which it favors privileged persons, and Marxist, because it will have buried the separation of capital and labor in the bin of history, and Keynesian, globally Keynesian.
But above everything else, it's a world where we can imagine a real democracy.
Will we awaken in such a world
Or will we sink into a "matrix"-like dystopia?
The answer depends on how we decide politically together.
It's in our hands, and we better do it democratically.
Thank you.
