I also know a lot of difficulties with data. I work in computer-assisted genetics -- an area where some very smart people use unimaginably a lot of data to make serious decisions, such as choosing cancer therapy
or the development of a drug. Over the years, I have identified some patterns about the difference between successful decisions based on data and unsuccessful decisions. This pattern should be spread.
If you ever need to solve a complex problem, you mainly do two things:
First, break this problem into its individual parts so that you can analyze the items; second, put the items back together to make a decision.
Sometimes you have to do this several times, but it's always two things: take it apart and put it back together.
And now the most important thing: data and data analysis are only good for the first part.
Data and data analysis, no matter how powerful, can only help to break down a problem and understand its parts.
They are not suitable for putting the parts back together and then coming to a decision.
There is another tool for this and we all own it: our brain.
If there is something the brain is good at, it is to put parts and pieces back together, even if the information is incomplete, then to make a good decision -- especially if it's an expert's brain.
